title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Examples behavior contributes positive environment community include: Demonstrating empathy kindness toward people respectful differing opinions, viewpoints, experiences Giving gracefully accepting constructive feedback Accepting responsibility apologizing affected mistakes, learning experience Focusing best just us individuals, overall community Examples unacceptable behavior include: use sexualized language imagery, sexual attention advances kind Trolling, insulting derogatory comments, personal political attacks Public private harassment Publishing others’ private information, physical email address, without explicit permission conduct reasonably considered inappropriate professional setting

title: Actions & Buttons
text: instance can use e_zoom action zoom graph (requires e_datazoom initialised).
code: cars |>    e_charts(dist) |>    e_scatter(speed) |>    e_datazoom() |>    e_zoom(     dataZoomIndex = 0,     start = 20,     end = 40   )

title: Actions & Buttons
text: Add button let user trigger action. add button e_button specify id button action (e_zoom) button knows action trigger. can also create button elsewhere document, long id matches btn. create button id matching event (graphButton). Note means button document must bear unique id. can also pass multiple buttons change positions.
code: cars |>    e_charts(dist) |>    e_scatter(speed) |>    e_datazoom() |>    e_zoom(     dataZoomIndex = 0,     start = 20,     end = 40,     btn = "BUTTON"   ) |>    e_button(     id = "BUTTON",      htmltools::tags$i(class = "fa fa-search"), # passed to the button     class = "btn btn-default",     "Zoom in"   ) value <- rnorm(10, 10, 2)  nodes <- data.frame(   name = sample(LETTERS, 10),   value = value,   size = value,   grp = rep(c("grp1", "grp2"), 5),   stringsAsFactors = FALSE )  edges <- data.frame(   source = sample(nodes$name, 20, replace = TRUE),   target = sample(nodes$name, 20, replace = TRUE),   stringsAsFactors = FALSE )  e_charts() |>    e_graph() |>    e_graph_nodes(nodes, name, value, size, grp) |>    e_graph_edges(edges, source, target) |>    e_focus_adjacency(     seriesIndex = 0,     dataIndex = 4,     btn = "graphButton"   ) # create the button htmltools::tags$a(   id = "graphButton",   class = "btn btn-primary",   "Highlight node #4" ) iris |>    group_by(Species) |>    e_charts(Sepal.Length) |>    e_line(Petal.Length) |>    e_datazoom() |>    e_highlight(series_name = "setosa", btn = "highlightButton") |> # highlight action   e_zoom( # zoom action     dataZoomIndex = 0,     startValue = 4,     endValue = 6,     btn = "zoomBtn"   ) |>    e_button(     id = "zoomBtn",     position = "bottom",     class = "btn btn-primary",     "Zoom"   ) |>    e_button(     "highlightButton",     position = "bottom",     class = "btn btn-default",     "highlight"   )

title: Actions & Buttons
text: Actions (can tied buttons): e_highlight & e_downplay highlight downplay serie. e_showtip & e_hidetip show hide tooltip. e_zoom zoom part graph. e_visual_map_range select part e_visual_map. e_pie_select & e_pie_unselect select unselect pie slices. e_focus_adjacency & e_unfocus_adjacency focus unfocus nodes graph. e_legend_scroll, e_legend_toggle_select, e_legend_unselect & e_legend_select interact legend. e_restore restore chart. e_map_select, e_map_unselect & e_map_toggle_select change maps.

title: Advanced
text: can set two common options e_common: Font family Theme charts page use Raleway font (sourced CSS Google fonts).
code: e_common(   font_family = "Raleway",   theme = NULL )

title: Advanced
text: package also understands dplyr::group_by order avoid add many layers manually one one. echarts4r essentially plot one serie group. plot one line (e_line) group (group_by). one exception, since 0.2.1, timeline set TRUE chart initialised e_charts. latter case group used step timeline.
code: iris |>    group_by(Species) |>    e_charts(Sepal.Length) |>    e_line(Sepal.Width) |>    e_title("Grouped data") iris |>    group_by(Species) |>    e_charts(Sepal.Length, timeline = TRUE) |>    e_line(Sepal.Width) |>    e_title("Timeline")

title: Advanced
code: df <- data.frame(   x = LETTERS[1:10],   a = runif(10),   b = runif(10),   c = runif(10),   d = runif(10) )  df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_bar(a, stack = "grp") |>    e_bar(b, stack = "grp") |>    e_bar(c, stack = "grp2") |>    e_bar(d, stack = "grp2")

title: Advanced
text: Since 0.2.0 e_scatter e_effect_scatter functions take different, much improved scale argument scaling function. default scaling function e_scale rescales 1 20, can pass . scaling function take vector integer numeric return similar vector length. instance, create function rescales 5 30: also works R 4.1.0 syntax. size passed size points defined symbol_size. size passed symbol_size becomes multiplier executed scaling function run. instance \(\log(1+x)*5\) behaviour added important able scale points within reasonable range, ideally points 1 30~40 size. Note rescaling color means also rescale e_visual_map, used. want keep original size can use scale_js, might want e_visual_map remain true original data. way bubbles appropriate size range visual map remains true.
code: iris |>      group_by(Species) |>      e_charts(Sepal.Length) |>      e_scatter(Petal.Length, Sepal.Width) my_scale <- function(x){   scales::rescale(x, to = c(5, 30)) }  iris |>      group_by(Species) |>      e_charts(Sepal.Length) |>      e_scatter(Petal.Length, Sepal.Width, scale = my_scale) iris |>       group_by(Species) |>      e_charts(Sepal.Length) |>      e_scatter(       Petal.Length,        Sepal.Width,        scale = \(x) scales::rescale(x, to = c(5, 30))     ) iris |>      group_by(Species) |>      e_charts(Sepal.Length) |>      e_scatter(Petal.Length, symbol_size = 15) iris |>      group_by(Species) |>      e_charts(Sepal.Length) |>      e_scatter(Petal.Length, Sepal.Width, scale = log1p, symbol_size = 10) echart <- mtcars |>    e_charts(mpg) |>    e_scatter(qsec, wt, scale = e_scale) |>    e_legend(show = FALSE)  echart |>    e_visual_map(wt, scale = e_scale) # or  # echart |>  #   e_visual_map(min = 1, max = 20) mtcars |>    e_charts(mpg) |>    e_scatter(qsec, wt, scale = NULL, scale_js = "function(data){ return data[3] * 3;}") |>    e_legend(show = FALSE) |>    e_visual_map(wt, scale = NULL)

title: Advanced
text: Since version 0.2.1 can jitter points e_scatter.
code: mtcars |>    e_charts(cyl) |>    e_scatter(drat, symbol_size = 4) |>    e_scatter(     drat, jitter_factor = 2, symbol_size = 6,     name = "noisy"   )

title: Advanced
text: Chart types applicable standard 2D cartesian coordinate system, though charts default cartesian2d coordinate system, may applied others. Let’s look heatmap. First regular heatmap. One also plot heatmap different coordinates, calendar first adding calendar e_calendar specifying coord_system = "calendar". Another example, using polar coordinates, plot line 2D cartesian coordinates, change polar. numerous coordinate system available echarts4r; globe, cartesian3d polar name . Note one coord_system available latter documented examples respective function’s man page.
code: v <- LETTERS[1:10] matrix <- data.frame(   x = sample(v, 300, replace = TRUE),    y = sample(v, 300, replace = TRUE),    z = rnorm(300, 10, 1),   stringsAsFactors = FALSE ) |>    dplyr::group_by(x, y) |>    dplyr::summarise(z = sum(z)) |>    dplyr::ungroup() #> `summarise()` has grouped output by 'x'. You can override using the `.groups` #> argument.  matrix |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_heatmap(y, z) |>    e_visual_map(z) dates <- seq.Date(as.Date("2018-01-01"), as.Date("2018-12-31"), by = "day") values <- rnorm(length(dates), 20, 6)  year <- data.frame(date = dates, values = values)  year |>    e_charts(date) |>    e_calendar(range = "2018") |>    e_heatmap(values, coord_system = "calendar") |>    e_visual_map(max = 30) df <- data.frame(x = 1:10, y = seq(1, 20, by = 2))  df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(y) df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_polar() |>    e_angle_axis() |>    e_radius_axis() |>    e_line(y, coord_system = "polar", smooth = TRUE)

title: Advanced
text: Use multiple axis, speecifying index axis. Note JavaScript starts 0 1, y_index = 1 second axis, y_index = 0 first axis (default)
code: USArrests |>    e_charts(Assault) |>    e_line(Murder, smooth = TRUE) |>    e_line(Rape, y_index = 1) |>  # add secondary axis   e_y_axis(splitLine = list(show = FALSE)) # hide split lines on first Y axis

title: Advanced
text: can flip coordinates e_flip_coords, note work multiple y axis.
code: data.frame(   x = LETTERS[1:5],   y = runif(5, 1, 15) ) |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_bar(y, name = "flipped") |>    e_flip_coords() # flip axis

title: Advanced
text: Highlight points lines plot e_mark family functions.
code: USArrests |>    tibble::rownames_to_column("State") |>    dplyr::mutate(     Rape = -Rape   ) |>    e_charts(State) |>    e_area(Murder) |>   e_bar(Rape, name = "Sick basterd", x_index = 1) |> # second y axis    e_mark_line("Sick basterd", data = list(type = "average")) |>    e_mark_point("Murder", data = list(type = "min"))

title: Advanced
text: Look arguments, echarts4r often one argument away want. radial:
code: library(dplyr) #>  #> Attaching package: 'dplyr' #> The following objects are masked from 'package:stats': #>  #>     filter, lag #> The following objects are masked from 'package:base': #>  #>     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union df <- tibble(   name = "earth",        # 1st level   children = list(     tibble(name = c("land", "ocean"),             # 2nd level        children = list(          tibble(name = c("forest", "river")),   # 3rd level           tibble(name = c("fish", "kelp"),             children = list(                tibble(name = c("shark", "tuna"),  # 4th level                 NULL  # kelp             ))          )        ))   ) )  df |>    e_charts() |>    e_tree() df |>    e_charts() |>    e_tree(layout = "radial")

title: Advanced
text: can, series show labels like : also helper function provides easier API
code: USArrests |>    tibble::rownames_to_column("State") |>    dplyr::slice(1:10) |>    e_charts(State) |>    e_area(Murder, label = list(normal = list(show = TRUE))) USArrests |>    tibble::rownames_to_column("State") |>    dplyr::slice(1:10) |>    e_charts(State) |>    e_area(Murder) |>    e_labels()

title: Advanced
text: might observe official documentation series can take data points just x y points, like e_bar; official documentation go “serie”, select one interested (.e.: bar) select “data”. e_bar lets pass serie (initial data.frame) corresponds value original library. However latter also takes, label, itemStyle, tooltip JSON arrays translate lists R dealing nested data.frames ideal. e_add_nested remedies . allows adding nested data points. Let’s add columns iris dataset use e_add_nested customize appearance label. Another example e_funnel.
code: # add columns to iris iris_dat <- iris |>    dplyr::mutate(     show = TRUE, # to show the labels     fontSize = exp(Sepal.Length) / 10, # font size will correspond to Sepal.Length     color = sample(c("red", "black", "blue"), dplyr::n(), replace = TRUE) # assign a random color to the label   )  iris_dat |>    dplyr::slice(1:10) |> # simplify the graph.    e_charts(Sepal.Width) |>    e_line(Sepal.Length) |>    e_add_nested("label", show, fontSize, color) |> # add our columns to "label"   e_x_axis(min = 2.5) funnel <- data.frame(   stage = c("View", "Click", "Purchase"),    value = c(80, 30, 20),   color = c("blue", "red", "green") )  funnel |>    e_charts() |>    e_funnel(value, stage) |>    e_add_nested("itemStyle", color)

title: Advanced
text: Since version 0.2.1 can pass raw list options. e_list can also used append options.
code: N <- 20 # data points  opts <- list(   xAxis = list(     type = "category",     data = LETTERS[1:N]   ),   yAxis = list(     type = "value"   ),   series = list(     list(       type = "line",       data = round(runif(N, 5, 20))     )   ) )  e_charts() |>    e_list(opts)

title: Brush & Slide
text: Let’s fairly standard chart add slider x axis one y axis.
code: mtcars |>    e_charts(mpg) |>    e_line(qsec) |>    e_datazoom(x_index = 0, type = "slider") |>    e_datazoom(y_index = 0, type = "slider")

title: Brush & Slide
text: Let’s leverage e_datazoom.
code: USArrests |>    e_charts(UrbanPop) |>    e_line(Assault) |>    e_area(Murder, y_index = 1, x_index = 1) |>    e_y_axis(gridIndex = 1) |>   e_x_axis(gridIndex = 1) |>    e_grid(height = "35%") |>    e_grid(height = "35%", top = "50%") |>    e_datazoom(x_index = c(0, 1))

title: Brush & Slide
text: Let’s now look e_brush. key 1) use bind argument e_scatter bind data, case stations, think key, 2) removing axis first e_scatter. Let’s combine . e_brush actually filters e_datazoom zooms data.
code: quakes |>    e_charts(long) |>    e_geo(       boundingCoords = list(           c(190, -10),           c(180, -40)       )   ) |>    e_scatter(lat, mag, stations, coord_system = "geo", name = "mag", rm_y = FALSE, rm_x = FALSE) |> # do not remove axis   e_data(quakes, depth) |> # use e_data to add data and/or change value on x axis   e_scatter(depth, mag, stations,  name = "mag & depth") |>  # plot scatter   e_grid(right = 40, top = 100, width = "30%") |> # adjust grid to avoid overlap   e_y_axis(name = "depth", min = 3.5) |> # add y axis name   e_x_axis(name = "magnitude") |> # add x axis name   e_legend(FALSE) |>  # hide legend   e_title("Built-in crosstalk", "Use the brush") |> # title   e_theme("westeros") |> # add a theme   e_brush() |> # add the brush   e_tooltip() # Add tooltips quakes |>    e_charts(long) |>    e_geo(       boundingCoords = list(           c(190, -10),           c(180, -40)       )   ) |>    e_scatter(lat, mag, stations, coord_system = "geo", name = "mag", rm_y = FALSE, rm_x = FALSE) |> # do not remove axis   e_data(quakes, depth) |> # use e_data to add data and/or change value on x axis   e_scatter(depth, mag, stations, name = "mag & depth") |>  # plot scatter   e_grid(right = 40, top = 100, width = "30%") |> # adjust grid to avoid overlap   e_y_axis(name = "depth", min = 3.5) |> # add y axis name   e_x_axis(name = "magnitude") |> # add x axis name   e_legend(FALSE) |>  # hide legend   e_title("Built-in crosstalk", "Use the brush") |> # title   e_theme("chalk") |> # add a theme   e_brush() |> # add the brush   e_tooltip() |>    e_datazoom(x_index = 0, type = "slider") |>    e_datazoom(y_index = 0, type = "slider")

title: Arrange & Connect
text: Since version 0.1.2 can connect multiple two charts together might make even easier. create two charts, e_datazoom, hiding one latter. second chart run e_connect connect ; sliders now linked. can link charts together two different ways, one e_connect refering charts’s id (elementId) can browse console like . package natively links interactions, therefore, following legend acutally unique, one legend trigger charts bear name. can connect pretty much anything, including geospatial visualisations, ’ll work long share one thing common (.e.: serie name). geo-spatial visualisations can slide visual map filter states/kingdoms (e_visual_map defaults calculable = TRUE).
code: e1 <- mtcars |>    e_charts(     mpg,     height = 200,     elementId = "chart1" # specify id   ) |>    e_scatter(wt) |>    e_datazoom(show = FALSE) # hide  e2 <- mtcars |>    e_charts(     wt,     height = 200,     elementId = "chart2" # specify id   ) |>    e_scatter(qsec) |>    e_datazoom(show = FALSE) # hide    e3 <- mtcars |>    e_charts(     qsec,     height = 200   ) |>    e_scatter(hp) |>    e_datazoom() |>    e_connect(c("chart1", "chart2")) # connect e_arrange(e1, e2, e3) create_chart <- function(data, var){   data |>      e_charts_(         "mpg",         height = 200     ) |>      e_scatter_(var, name = "Click me!") |>      e_group("4charts") # all charts in the same group } e4 <- create_chart(mtcars, "hp") e5 <- create_chart(mtcars, "wt") e6 <- create_chart(mtcars, "drat") e7 <- create_chart(mtcars, "qsec") |>    e_connect_group("4charts") # connect charts  e_arrange(e4, e5, e6, e7, rows = 2, cols = 2) library(echarts4r.maps)  USArrests$state <- row.names(USArrests)  e8 <- USArrests |>    e_charts(state, elementId = "US") |>   em_map("USA") |>    e_map_3d(Murder, map = "USA", name = "Murder", boxWidth = 70) |>    e_visual_map(Murder)  # this is made up UK <- data.frame(   kingdoms = c("England", "Wales", "Nothern Ireland", "Scotland"),   murder = c(.8, 5, 13.2, 17.4) )  e9 <- UK |>    e_charts(kingdoms) |>   em_map("United_Kingdom") |>    e_map_3d(murder, map = "United_Kingdom", name = "Murder", boxWidth = 50) |>    e_visual_map(murder, show = FALSE) |>    e_connect("US")  e_arrange(e8, e9, cols = 2, rows = 1)

title: Arrange & Connect
text: need e_arrange Shiny, though e_connect e_arrange work hand hand can use one without . fact don’t truly use e_arrange R markdown either. charts connected don’t need side side.
code: library(shiny) library(echarts4r)  ui <- fluidPage(   fluidRow(   column(5, echarts4rOutput("plot1")),   column(2, "Charts are connected, no need for", code("e_arrange")),   column(5, echarts4rOutput("plot2"))   ) )  server <- function(input, output, session) {      output$plot1 <- renderEcharts4r({     cars |>        e_charts(         speed,         height = 200       ) |>        e_scatter(dist, name = "legend") |>        e_datazoom(show = FALSE, y_index = 0) |>        e_group("grp")   })      output$plot2 <- renderEcharts4r({     cars |>        e_charts(         dist,         height = 200       ) |>        e_scatter(speed, name = "legend") |>        e_datazoom(y_index = 0) |>        e_group("grp") |>  # assign group       e_connect_group("grp")   })    }  shinyApp(ui, server)

title: Get Started
text: Thanks Sharon Machlis amazing video article introducing echarts4r.

title: Get Started
text: Let’s build line chart, load library pipe data e_charts. ease |> can use e_charts(mtcars, wt). ease bare column names can use escape hatches ending _. easiest way use |> operator add plots options.
code: # prepare data df <- state.x77 |>    as.data.frame() |>    tibble::rownames_to_column("State") library(echarts4r) # load echarts4r  df |>    e_charts(x = State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(serie = Population) # add a line df |>    e_charts_("State") |>    e_line_("Population") df |>    e_charts(State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(Population) |>  # add a line   e_area(Income) # add area

title: Get Started
text: also change lines make smooth. Lets label axes convenience function e_axis_labels. can use one 13 built-themes, see ?e_theme complete list, ’ll also add title e_title. legend title bit close, let’s move legend another part canvas. Add tooltip, numerous options, use trigger = "axis" trigger tooltip axis rather single data point. Finally, currently plotting population income axis, let’s put respective y axis specifying extra axis Income. Dual y axes terrible idea, ’s demonstration purposes.
code: df |>    e_charts(State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(Population, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add a line   e_area(Income, smooth = TRUE) # add area df |>    e_charts(State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(Population, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add a line   e_area(Income, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add area   e_axis_labels(x = "State") # axis labels df |>    e_charts(State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(Population, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add a line   e_area(Income, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add area   e_axis_labels(x = "State") |> # axis labels   e_title("US States", "Population & Income") |>  # Add title & subtitle   e_theme("infographic") # theme df |>    e_charts(State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(Population, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add a line   e_area(Income, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add area   e_axis_labels(x = "State") |> # axis labels   e_title("US States", "Population & Income") |>  # Add title & subtitle   e_theme("infographic") |>  # theme   e_legend(right = 0) # move legend to the bottom df |>    e_charts(State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(Population, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add a line   e_area(Income, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add area   e_axis_labels(x = "State") |> # axis labels   e_title("US States", "Population & Income") |>  # Add title & subtitle   e_theme("infographic") |>  # theme   e_legend(right = 0) |>  # move legend to the bottom   e_tooltip(trigger = "axis") # tooltip df |>    e_charts(State) |> # initialise and set x   e_line(Population, smooth = TRUE) |>  # add a line   e_area(Income, smooth = TRUE, y_index = 1) |>  # add area   e_axis_labels(x = "State") |> # axis labels   e_title("US States", "Population & Income") |>  # Add title & subtitle   e_theme("infographic") |>  # theme   e_legend(right = 0) |>  # move legend to the bottom   e_tooltip(trigger = "axis") # tooltip

title: web GL
text: Van der Pol oscillator David Granjon. can also plot different coordinates (coord_system).
code: vectors <- expand.grid(x = -3:3, y = -3:3) mu <- 1 vectors$sx <- vectors$y vectors$sy <- mu * (1 - vectors$x^2) * vectors$y - vectors$x vectors$color <- log10(runif(nrow(vectors), 1, 10))  vectors |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_flow_gl(y, sx, sy, color) |>    e_visual_map(     min = 0, max = 1, # log 10     dimension = 4, # x = 0, y = 1, sx = 3, sy = 4     show = FALSE, # hide     inRange = list(       color = c('#313695', '#4575b4', '#74add1', '#abd9e9', '#e0f3f8',                 '#ffffbf', '#fee090', '#fdae61', '#f46d43', '#d73027', '#a50026')     )   ) |>    e_x_axis(     splitLine = list(show = FALSE)   ) |>    e_y_axis(     splitLine = list(show = FALSE)   ) latlong <- seq(-180, 180, by = 5) wind = expand.grid(lng = latlong, lat = latlong) wind$slng <- rnorm(nrow(wind), 0, 200) wind$slat <- rnorm(nrow(wind), 0, 200) wind$color <- abs(wind$slat) - abs(wind$slng)  trans <- list(opacity = 0.5) # transparency  wind |>    e_charts(lng, backgroundColor = '#333') |>    e_geo(     itemStyle = list(       normal = list(         areaColor = "#323c48",         borderColor = "#111"       )     )   ) |>    e_flow_gl(     lat, slng, slat, color,      itemStyle = trans,     particleSize = 2   ) |>    e_visual_map(     color, # range     dimension = 4, # lng = 0, lat = 1, slng = 2, slat = 3, color = 4     show = FALSE, # hide     inRange = list(       color = c('#313695', '#4575b4', '#74add1', '#abd9e9', '#e0f3f8',                  '#ffffbf', '#fee090', '#fdae61', '#f46d43', '#d73027', '#a50026')     )   ) |>    e_x_axis(show = FALSE) |>    e_y_axis(show = FALSE)

code: flights <- read.csv(   paste0("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plotly/datasets/",          "master/2011_february_aa_flight_paths.csv") ) |>    dplyr::select(airport1, airport2)  airports <- read.csv(   paste0("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plotly/datasets/",          "master/2011_february_us_airport_traffic.csv") ) |>    dplyr::select(iata, cnt)  # remove airports with no flights airp <- unique(c(as.character(flights$airport1), as.character(flights$airport2))) airports <- airports |>    dplyr::filter(iata %in% airp)  e_charts() |>      e_graph_gl() |>      e_graph_nodes(airports, iata, cnt) |>      e_graph_edges(flights, airport1, airport2) |>      e_modularity() |>      e_tooltip()

text: Les Miserables dataset popular visualization demonstrates network graphs. example graph provided .
code: library(echarts4r)  les <- jsonlite::fromJSON("https://gist.githubusercontent.com/tylerlittlefield/0d7a53f2a1f55cb3c6ffe22c67618267/raw/0684a839c3e49dac1157721ddd906eff8f9491d4/les-miserables.json")   e_charts() |>    e_graph(     layout = "circular",      circular = list(       rotateLabel = TRUE     ),     roam = TRUE,     lineStyle = list(       color = "source",       curveness = 0.3     ),     label = list(       position = "right",       formatter = "{b}"     )   ) |>   e_graph_nodes(     nodes = les$nodes,      names = name,      value = value,      size = size,      category = grp   ) |>    e_graph_edges(     edges = les$edges,      source = from,     target = to   ) |>   e_tooltip()

title: Grid & Axis
text: can customise axis e_axis, e_x_axis e_y_axis, can see official documentation details. also helper function, e_format_axis sisters e_format_x_axis e_format_y_axis. latter lets easily add suffix prefix axis labels. Say want plot ceslius. Since version 0.2.1 can also easily format axis decimal, percentages currencies thanks contribution Artem Klevtsov.
code: df <- data.frame(   x = 1:20, # celsius   y = runif(20, 1, 100) # percentages )  df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(y) |>    e_format_x_axis(suffix = "°C") |>    e_legend(FALSE) df |>    dplyr::mutate(y = y / 100) |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(y, legend = FALSE) |>    e_x_axis(     formatter = e_axis_formatter("currency", currency = "GBP")   ) |>    e_y_axis(     formatter = e_axis_formatter("decimal", digits = 3)   )

title: Grid & Axis
text: can also customise grid , instance, multiple plots one canvas. Let’s initialise basic plot. Now say don’t want w z plot. course make two entirely different plots (2 plots initialised e_charts()), cleaner canvas, bit like ggplot2 facets. First two plots canvas means multiple axis, ’ll plot serie axis. echarts4r R API JavaScript library, arrays start one; x y indices default 0 need change one series’ indices 1. Therefore one serie plotted index 0 index 1 two xand y axis. Notice echarts4r puts additional axis top right plot. useful feature want; ’re missing split grid. use e_grid twice two grids, define height ; 35% ideal stacked grids, need margin legend, axis, etc. hence using 50%. However, still line plots grid. think grids axis echarts4r. series (.e.: e_line) plotted axis (e_axis) axis plotted grids e_grid two grids two axis axis plotted grid(point #2 ). need move two additional axis another grid. Note grid indices also start 0 . go! can also different grid put plots side side.
code: df <- data.frame(   x = 1:20,    w = runif(20, 1, 100),   z = runif(20, 25, 75) )  df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(w) |>    e_line(z) df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(w) |>    e_line(z, x_index = 1, y_index = 1) df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(w) |>    e_line(z, x_index = 1, y_index = 1) |>    e_grid(height = "35%") |> # two grids of 35% height   e_grid(height = "35%", top = "50%") # this grid is 50% from the top df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(w) |>    e_line(z, x_index = 1, y_index = 1) |>    e_grid(height = "35%") |>    e_grid(height = "35%", top = "50%") |>    e_y_axis(gridIndex = 1) |> # put x and y on grid index 1   e_x_axis(gridIndex = 1) df |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_line(w) |>    e_line(z, x_index = 1, y_index = 1) |>    e_grid(width = "35%") |>    e_grid(width = "35%", left = "55%") |>    e_y_axis(gridIndex = 1) |> # put x and y on grid index 1   e_x_axis(gridIndex = 1)

title: GeoJSON data
text: Get India map data gadm website, command need network available, download rds data current directory. Note can combine maps raster::union(map1, map2) em_maps function echarts4r.maps package. convert SpatialPolygonsDataFrame GeoJSON geojsonio: take long time map detailed. Therefore can simplify map make smaller. function raster::getData gives polygon NAME_* property (* level specified) rather just name. tooltip display properly unless use nameMap point property, default echarts expects name property. Now can use GeoJSON e_map_register.
code: india_sp <- raster::getData('GADM', country = 'INDIA', level = 2)  #> Warning in raster::getData("GADM", country = "INDIA", level = 2): getData will be removed in a future version of raster #> . Please use the geodata package instead india_sp |>    head() |>    knitr::kable() india_json <- geojsonio::geojson_list(india_sp) print(object.size(india_json), units = "Mb") #> 59.6 Mb india_small <- rmapshaper::ms_simplify(india_sp, keep = 0.05)  india_json_small <- geojsonio::geojson_list(india_small) print(object.size(india_json_small), units = "Mb")  #> 6.8 Mb # plot  e_charts() |>   e_map_register("India", india_json_small) |>   e_map(map = "India", nameProperty = "NAME_2")

title: Proxies
text: essentially covers consequential new feature echarts4r allows using function adds serie chart (e.g.: e_bar) proxy. , combined new e_remove_serie lets one seamlessly add remove series chart without redraw entirety, making much slicker Shiny charts.

title: Proxies
text: basic Shiny application uses echarts4r. ’ll afterwards add app ability add remove serie. add button enable adding serie chart. Create proxy echarts4rProxy. use e_line add scatter plot. Actually update chart e_execute. First, means can now use echarts4rProxy just like nearly chart initialisation function e_charts. used e_line free use functions adds serie chart. e_execute function used actually send updates front end chart updated, allows batching updates, e.g.: add scatter plot line .  can add another button remove serie e_remove_serie require use e_execute.  can now demonstrate add multiple series, useful e_execute.
code: library(shiny) library(echarts4r)  # phoney data df <- data.frame(   x = 1:100,   y = runif(100),   z = runif(100) )  ui <- fluidPage(   echarts4rOutput("chart") )  server <- function(input, output){    output$chart <- renderEcharts4r({     e_charts(df, x) |>        e_scatter(y, z)   })  }  shinyApp(ui, server) library(shiny) library(echarts4r)  # phoney data df <- data.frame(   x = 1:100,   y = runif(100),   z = runif(100) )  ui <- fluidPage(   actionButton("add", "Add z serie"), # button   echarts4rOutput("chart") )  server <- function(input, output){    output$chart <- renderEcharts4r({     e_charts(df, x) |>        e_scatter(y, z)   })    observeEvent(input$add, {     echarts4rProxy("chart", data = df, x = x) |>  # create a proxy       e_line(z) |>        e_execute()   })  }  shinyApp(ui, server) library(shiny) library(echarts4r)  # phoney data df <- data.frame(   x = 1:100,   y = runif(100),   z = runif(100) )  ui <- fluidPage(   actionButton("add", "Add z serie"),    actionButton("rm", "Remove z serie"),    echarts4rOutput("chart") )  server <- function(input, output){    output$chart <- renderEcharts4r({     e_charts(df, x) |>        e_scatter(y, z)   })    observeEvent(input$add, {     echarts4rProxy("chart", data = df, x = x) |>  # create a proxy       e_line(z) |>        e_execute()   })    observeEvent(input$rm, {     echarts4rProxy("chart") |>  # create a proxy       e_remove_serie("z")   })  }  shinyApp(ui, server) library(shiny) library(echarts4r)  # phoney data df <- data.frame(   x = 1:100,   y = runif(100),   z = runif(100) )  ui <- fluidPage(   actionButton("add", "Add series"),    actionButton("rm", "Remove series"),    echarts4rOutput("chart") )   server <- function(input, output){    output$chart <- renderEcharts4r({     e_charts(df, x) |>        e_scatter(y, z)   })    observeEvent(input$add, {     echarts4rProxy("chart", data = df, x = x) |>  # create a proxy       e_line(z) |>        e_loess(y ~ x, name = "fit") |>        e_execute()   })    observeEvent(input$rm, {     echarts4rProxy("chart") |>  # create a proxy       e_remove_serie("z") |>        e_remove_serie("fit")   })  }  shinyApp(ui, server)

title: Shiny
text: Get data shiny following: elementId + _brush - returns data brushed data points. elementId + _legend_change - returns series name legend selected/unselected. elementId + _legend_selected - returns list selected status series. elementId + _clicked_data - returns data clicked data point. elementId + _clicked_data_value - returns value clicked data point. elementId + _clicked_row - returns row number clicked data point. elementId + _clicked_serie - returns name serie clicked data point. elementId + _mouseover_data - returns data hovered data point. elementId + _mouseover_data_value - returns value hovered data point. elementId + _mouseover_row - returns row o hovered data point. elementId + _mouseover_serie - returns name serie hovered data point. want implement missing callback e_distpatch_action_p. Paul Simmering kindly created demo app showcasing callbacks. Callbacks demo

title: Shiny
text: Interact charts without redrawing (proxies): e_append1_p e_append2_p - add data chart. e_highlight_p e_downplay_p - highlight downplay serie. e_showtip_p e_hidetip_p - Show hide tooltip. e_draw_p draw chart, see function documentation examples. e_focus_adjacency e_unfocus_adjacency - focus unfocus adjacent nodes (networks). e_mark_p dynamically mark points, lines, areas. See example various proxies documentation.
code: library(shiny) library(echarts4r)  ui <- fluidPage(   actionButton("add", "Add Data to y"),   echarts4rOutput("plot"),   verbatimTextOutput("selected") )  server <- function(input, output, session){    data <- data.frame(x = rnorm(10, 5, 3), y = rnorm(10, 50, 12), z = rnorm(10, 50, 5))      react <- eventReactive(input$add, {     set.seed(sample(1:1000, 1))     data.frame(x = rnorm(10, 5, 2), y = rnorm(10, 50, 10))   })      output$plot <- renderEcharts4r({     data |>       e_charts(x) |>       e_scatter(y) |>      e_scatter(z) |>       e_brush(throttleDelay = 1000)   })      observeEvent(input$add, {     echarts4rProxy("plot") |>        e_append1_p(0, react(), x, y)   })      output$selected <- renderPrint({     input$plot_brush   })    }  shinyApp(ui, server)

title: Shiny

code: # no redraw # no loading library(shiny) ui <- fluidPage(   fluidRow(     column(12, actionButton("update", "Update"))   ),   fluidRow(     column(12, echarts4rOutput("plot"))   ) )  server <- function(input, output){   data <- eventReactive(input$update, {     data.frame(       x = 1:10,       y = rnorm(10)     )   })      output$plot <- renderEcharts4r({     data() |>        e_charts(x) |>        e_bar(y)   }) }  shinyApp(ui, server) # keep UI # add loading server <- function(input, output){   data <- eventReactive(input$update, {     Sys.sleep(1) # sleep one second to show loading     data.frame(       x = 1:10,       y = rnorm(10)     )   })      output$plot <- renderEcharts4r({     data() |>        e_charts(x) |>        e_bar(y) |>        e_show_loading()   }) }  shinyApp(ui, server)

title: Themes
text: admittedly small theme, want create large custom theme, download JSON theme builder use , e_theme_custom e_register_theme detect json file read . method , however, registers theme every time chart drawn, displaying multiple charts can leads large html files slower Shiny application. thus also function e_theme_register register custom theme , subsequently use . Note custom theme registered works e_common, e.g.: e_common(theme = "myTheme").
code: p |> e_theme_custom('{"color":["#ff715e","#ffaf51"]}') // theme.json {   "color":["#ff715e","#ffaf51"],   "backgroundColor": "black" } # in R p |> e_theme_custom("theme.json") library(shiny) library(echarts4r)  ui <- fluidPage(   e_theme_register('{"color":["#ff715e","#ffaf51"]}', name = "myTheme"),   echarts4rOutput("chart1"),   echarts4rOutput("chart2") )  server <- function(input, output){   e <- e_charts(cars, speed) |>        e_scatter(dist)     output$chart1 <- renderEcharts4r({     e_theme(e, "myTheme")   })    output$chart2 <- renderEcharts4r({     e_theme(e, "myTheme")   })  }  shinyApp(ui, server)

title: Timeline
text: echarts4r version 0.2.1 supports timeline component! Let’s create phoney data demonstrate. “standard” chart group data distinguish categories, take advantage timeline component, group time steps set timeline TRUEwhen initialise chart. changing single argument (timeline) go : acutal timeline:
code: # fake data df <- data.frame(   year = c(     rep(2016, 25),     rep(2017, 25),     rep(2018, 25),     rep(2019, 25)   ),   x = rnorm(100),   y = rnorm(100),   grp = c(     rep("A", 50),     rep("B", 50)   ) ) df |>   group_by(year) |>    e_charts(x) |>    e_scatter(y, symbol_size = 5) df |>   group_by(year) |>    e_charts(x, timeline = TRUE) |>    e_scatter(y, symbol_size = 5)

title: Timeline
text: works vast majority chart types, listed man page e_charts. e_bar e_line e_step e_area e_scatter e_effect_scatter e_candle e_heatmap e_pie e_line_3d e_lines_3d e_bar_3d e_lines e_scatter_3d e_scatter_gl e_histogram e_lm e_loess e_glm e_density e_pictorial e_boxplot e_map e_map_3d e_line_3d e_gauge options, .e.: e_tooltip e_globe, work timeline component.
code: df |>    group_by(year) |>    e_charts(x, timeline = TRUE) |>    e_scatter(y) |>    e_loess(y ~ x)

title: Timeline
text: can pass options timeline e_timeline_opts.
code: library(dplyr) library(echarts4r.maps)  df <- USArrests  # scale 0 to 1 .scl <- function(x){     (x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)) }  df |>    tibble::rownames_to_column("State") |>    mutate(     Rape = .scl(Rape),     Murder = .scl(Murder),     Assault = .scl(Assault)   ) |>    select(State, Rape, Murder, Assault) |>    group_by(State) |>    tidyr::gather("Key",  "Value", Murder, Rape, Assault) |>    group_by(Key) |>    e_charts(State, timeline = TRUE) |>    em_map("USA") |>    e_map(Value, map = "USA") |>    e_visual_map(min = 0, max = 1) |>    e_timeline_opts(autoPlay = TRUE) |>    e_timeline_serie(     title = list(       list(text = "Assault", subtext = "Percentage based on arrests"),       list(text = "Murder", subtext = "Percentage based on arrests"),       list(text = "Rape", subtext = "Percentage based on arrests")     )   )

title: Timeline
text: function e_timeline_opts used set general options timeline, .e.: auto-play like . full list options official website. However, can also set options specific timestep e_timeline_serie. arguments function differ quite bit rest package. assign options multiple timesteps need pass vectors lists options, length timesteps.
code: library(quantmod)  getSymbols(c("GS", "GOOG")) # Goldman Sachs & Google #> [1] "GS"   "GOOG" GS <- as.data.frame(GS) GOOG <- as.data.frame(GOOG)  colnames <- c("Open", "High", "Low", "Close", "Volume", "Adjusted") names(GS) <- colnames names(GOOG) <- colnames  GS$sym <- "GS" GOOG$sym <- "GOOG"  data <- bind_rows(GS, GOOG) data$date <- rep(row.names(GS), 2)  data |>    group_by(sym) |>    e_charts(date, timeline = TRUE) |>    e_candle(Open, Close, Low, High, legend = FALSE) |>    e_y_axis(max = 1500) |>    e_tooltip(trigger = "axis") |>    e_timeline_opts(     axis_type = "category",     playInterval = 1500,     top = 5,     right = 50,     left = 200   ) |>    e_datazoom() |>    e_timeline_serie(     title = list(       list(text = "Goldman Sachs"),       list(text = "Google")     )   )

title: Tooltip
text: Thanks Sharon Machlis helping put document together. can display default tooltip adding e_tooltip() code creates visualization, Note can change trigger axis. order customize tooltip, ’ll need comfortable adding little JavaScript R code. Tooltip customization uses formatter. specific information ’d like appear goes within return(). ’s need know adding variables return() code: x-axis variable params.value[0]. y-axis variable params.value[1]. added another, size variable scatter plot, params.value[2]. (Note JavaScript, indexing starts 0 computer languages, 1 R.) ’s might customize tooltip scatter plot mtcars wt mpg, order show wt mpg tooltip: ’d like add information data frame column ’s included chart, can pass data using bind argument. example, might want include name car model tooltip. particular data set, ’d first need create column, can code mtcars <- tibble::rownames_to_column(mtcars, "model"). , can pass column scatter plot visualization e_scatter(mpg, bind = model).
code:
mtcars |> e_charts(wt) |> e_scatter(mpg, qsec) |> e_tooltip(trigger = "item") mtcars |> e_charts(wt) |> e_line(mpg) |> e_line(qsec) |> e_tooltip(trigger = "axis") e_tooltip( formatter = htmlwidgets::JS(" function(params){ return(); } ") ) mtcars |> e_charts(wt) |> e_scatter(mpg, qsec) |> e_tooltip(formatter = htmlwidgets::JS(" function(params){ return('wt: ' + params.value[0] + '
mpg: ' + params.value[1]) } ") ) mtcars |> tibble::rownames_to_column("model") |> e_charts(wt) |> e_scatter(mpg, qsec, bind = model) |> e_tooltip( formatter = htmlwidgets::JS(" function(params){ return('' + params.name + '
wt: ' + params.value[0] + '
mpg: ' + params.value[1]) } ") )

code: if (FALSE) { library(shiny)  ui <- fluidPage(   actionButton("add", "Add Data to y"),   echarts4rOutput("plot"),   h4("Brush"),   verbatimTextOutput("selected"),   h4("Legend select change"),   verbatimTextOutput("legend") )  server <- function(input, output, session) {   data <- data.frame(x = rnorm(10, 5, 3), y = rnorm(10, 50, 12), z = rnorm(10, 5, 20))    react <- eventReactive(input$add, {     set.seed(sample(1:1000, 1))     data.frame(x = rnorm(10, 5, 2), y = rnorm(10, 50, 10), z = rnorm(10, 5, 20))   })    output$plot <- renderEcharts4r({     data |>       e_charts(x) |>       e_scatter(y, z, scale = NULL) |>       e_scatter(z) |>       e_brush()   })    observeEvent(input$add, {     echarts4rProxy("plot") |>       e_append2_p(0, react(), x, y, z)   })    output$selected <- renderPrint({     input$plot_brush   })    output$legend <- renderPrint({     input$plot_legend_change   }) }  shinyApp(ui, server) }

title: Mark — e_mark_p
code: library(shiny) library(dplyr)  ui <- fluidPage(   fluidRow(     column(3, actionButton("pxy", "Marks")),     column(       3,       checkboxInput("tln", "Timeline", value = FALSE)     )   ),   echarts4rOutput("plot") )  server <- function(input, output) {   data(EuStockMarkets)    bb <- as.data.frame(EuStockMarkets) |>     slice_head(n = 150) |>     mutate(day = 1:n())    output$plot <- renderEcharts4r({     react()   })    observeEvent(input$pxy, {     echarts4rProxy("plot", data = NULL) |>       e_mark_p(         type = "line",         serie_index = 1,         data = list(type = "average"),         lineStyle = list(type = "dashed", color = "cyan")       ) |>       e_mark_p(         serie_index = 2,         data = list(           xAxis = bb$day[60],           yAxis = bb$SMI[60],           value = "pnt"         )       ) |>       e_mark_p(         type = "line",         serie_index = 2,         data = list(           list(xAxis = bb$day[10], yAxis = bb$SMI[10]),           list(xAxis = bb$day[37], yAxis = bb$SMI[37])         ),         lineStyle = list(type = "solid", color = "yellow")       ) |>       e_mark_p(         type = "area",         serie_index = 1,         data = list(           list(xAxis = bb$day[95]),           list(xAxis = bb$day[105])         ),         itemStyle = list(color = "lightblue"),         label = list(formatter = "X-area", position = "middle")       ) |>       e_merge()   })    react <- eventReactive(input$tln, {     tmp <- bb     if (input$tln) tmp <- tmp |> group_by(day < 75)      tmp |>       e_charts(         day,         backgroundColor = "#181818",         legend = list(textStyle = list(color = "#aaa")),         timeline = input$tln       ) |>       e_y_axis(scale = TRUE, axisLabel = list(color = "#aaa")) |>       e_line(CAC, symbol = "none", color = "#ff33b8") |>       e_line(SMI, symbol = "none", color = "green")   }) } if (interactive()) {   shinyApp(ui, server) }

code: library(shiny)  ui <- fluidPage(   actionButton("rm", "Remove z serie"),   echarts4rOutput("plot") )  server <- function(input, output, session) {   data <- data.frame(     x = rnorm(10, 5, 3),     y = rnorm(10, 50, 12),     z = rnorm(10, 50, 5)   )    output$plot <- renderEcharts4r({     data |>       e_charts(x) |>       e_scatter(y) |>       e_scatter(z)   })    observeEvent(input$rm, {     echarts4rProxy("plot") |>       e_remove_serie_p(serie_name = "z")   }) } if (FALSE) { shinyApp(ui, server) }

title: Sunburst — e_sunburst
text: Charts e_sunburst, e_treemap e_tree require hierarchical input data. structure represented thru json lists nested tibbles (data.frame). Input data may contain styles, see itemStyle examples jsonl df . number lists styles parameter match number elements names /levels. names levels present, name styles take precedence level styles. Multiple names may style, see c('land','river') . Multiple levels may style, see c(3,4) . styles lists contain items color, borderColor specified official documentation.

text: Must pass seriesId, seriesIndex, seriesName, generally seriesIndex = 0 work.

title: Node Adjacency — e_focus_adjacency_p
code: value <- rnorm(10, 10, 2)  nodes <- data.frame(   name = sample(LETTERS, 10),   value = value,   size = value,   grp = rep(c("grp1", "grp2"), 5),   stringsAsFactors = FALSE )  edges <- data.frame(   source = sample(nodes$name, 20, replace = TRUE),   target = sample(nodes$name, 20, replace = TRUE),   stringsAsFactors = FALSE ) if (FALSE) {  library(shiny)  ui <- fluidPage(   fluidRow(     column(       2,       numericInput("index", "Node", value = 3, min = 1, max = 9)     ),     column(       2,       br(),       actionButton("focus", "Focus")     ),     column(       2,       br(),       actionButton("unfocus", "Unfocus")     )   ),   fluidRow(     column(12, echarts4rOutput("graph"))   ) )  server <- function(input, output, session) {   output$graph <- renderEcharts4r({     e_charts() |>       e_graph() |>       e_graph_nodes(nodes, name, value, size, grp) |>       e_graph_edges(edges, source, target)   })    observeEvent(input$focus, {     echarts4rProxy("graph") |>       e_focus_adjacency_p(         seriesIndex = 0,         index = input$index       )   })    observeEvent(input$unfocus, {     echarts4rProxy("graph") |>       e_unfocus_adjacency_p(seriesIndex = 0)   }) }  if (interactive()) {   shinyApp(ui, server) } }

title: Tooltip Proxy — e_showtip_p
code: if (FALSE) { library(shiny)  ui <- fluidPage(   fluidRow(     actionButton("show", "Show tooltip"),     actionButton("hide", "Hide tooltip")   ),   fluidRow(     echarts4rOutput("plot"),     h3("clicked Data"),     verbatimTextOutput("clickedData"),     h3("clicked Serie"),     verbatimTextOutput("clickedSerie"),     h3("clicked Row"),     verbatimTextOutput("clickedRow")   ) )  server <- function(input, output, session) {   output$plot <- renderEcharts4r({     mtcars |>       e_charts(mpg) |>       e_line(disp, bind = carb, name = "displacement") |>       e_line(hp) |>       e_x_axis(min = 10) |>       e_tooltip(show = FALSE) |>       e_theme("westeros")   })    observeEvent(input$show, {     echarts4rProxy("plot") |>       e_showtip_p(         name = "displacement",         position = list(5, 5)       )   })    observeEvent(input$hide, {     echarts4rProxy("plot") |>       e_hidetip_p()   })    output$clickedData <- renderPrint({     input$plot_clicked_data   })    output$clickedSerie <- renderPrint({     input$plot_clicked_serie   })    output$clickedRow <- renderPrint({     input$plot_clicked_row   }) }  if (interactive()) {   shinyApp(ui, server) } }

title: echarts4r 0.4.4
text: CRAN release: 2022-05-28 Better checks theme names #407 Update echarts.js 5.3.2 Added e_morph

title: echarts4r 0.4.3
text: CRAN release: 2022-01-03 Bump echarts.js version 5.2.2 Support click plot background #394 e_get_zr. e_facet function completed #396 thanks Robert Koetsier

title: echarts4r 0.4.2
text: CRAN release: 2021-10-04 Added proxy method e_color, see #347 Added .serie argument e_add allow adding data specific serie. Added .data argument e_add. Added value size arguments e_graph_edges. Add note documentation clarify x axis type e_bar see #357 Update themes attempt fix #363 Update base JavaScript version Echarts.js v 5.1.2 Fix #365 e_flip_coords works data formats. Deprecate e_add favour e_add_nested e_add_unnested see ?nesting, see #371 Allow passing multiple names (vector) e_lm, one group. Bring support locales #372 one can automatically translate part plots.

title: echarts4r 0.4.1
text: CRAN release: 2021-07-14 Apply mark series timeline, fixes #290 Bump ECharts.js Add e_svg family functions fix #319 Replaced magrittr pipe %>% R native’s |>. Fix e_map used data, map displayed Fix e_flip_coords boxplots (single column series) see #336 Fix e_add applied timeline, see #338

title: echarts4r 0.4.0
text: CRAN release: 2021-03-07 Bump ECharts.js updated version 4 5.

title: echarts4r 0.3.4
text: Fixed naming x axis e_boxplot, see #219 Fixed e_parallel arguments, see #223 Accept data.tree data easy creation tree, treemaps sunbursts, see #207 Fix ordering timeline #234 Fix issue e_band() displays upper band incorrectly, see #237. Thanks @shrektan reporting PR.

title: echarts4r 0.3.3
text: CRAN release: 2020-10-16 Added echarts4rBox, renderEcharts4rBox, echarts4rBoxOutput create value boxes. Fix e_common theme, longer applied due dynamic dependencies introduced 0.3.2 Fix e_flip_coords timeline feature, see #166 name argument used e_boxplot, see #171 Allow customising area curve density plot see #172 Update mapbox dependency 0.38 1.11 Fix country name conversion e_country_names #189 Fix legend toggle radar charts #74 e_loess, e_lm take model_args argument pass arguments underlying model function #194 Bump JavaScript version 4.9.0 echarts_from_json supports functions, see 199 (thanks swsoyee) Remove e_facet, wrongly exported #212 Add tests, thanks Etienne Bacher, see #201 Add styler, thanks Wei Su see #211 Removed {d3r} import: longer necessary.

title: echarts4r 0.3.2
text: CRAN release: 2020-06-18 Bump echarts.js 4.8.0 echarts-gl 1.1.2 Fix e_add used timeline feature see #165. Bump echart.js 4.8.0 now english (longer Chinese). Dynamic dependencies: themes leaflet mapbox wordcloud liquidfill world.js (underlying world map e_geo e_map) error bars (custom renderer) greatly improves performances echarts4r now loads much faster.

title: echarts4r 0.3.1.9000
text: Added convenience e_hide_grid_lines easily hide grid lines. e_map_register_ui added register custom map Shiny UI, faster serialisation. e_leaflet* functions now correctly apply roam argument #147 Internals changes dplyr >= 0.7.0 Correct bug boxplot thanks Matthias issue #163 fix. Avoid page breaks PDF, see #159, thanks Steve.

title: echarts4r 0.3.0.9000
text: Bumped echarts JavaScript library 4.6.0, PR #121, also bumped echarts gl 1.2.1. Every function adds serie chart (e.g.: e_bar) turned methods now can applied proxies (echarts4rProxy), see development vignette . implies minute changes echarts4rProxy: nothing broken though. Warning e_axis_fomatter user uses RStudio, relates #100 Fixed #98 bug introduced e_radar_opts timeline component added. bind argument added e_heatmap e_scatter_3d correctly takes bind argument coords set cartesian3D (previously incorrect). Bumped number built-themes 40+. Added e_remove_serie_p remove series graph. Added e_axis_labels easily place axis labels. Added e_resize dynamically resize chart. Added e_map_register_p works like proxy require chart. Fixed issues e_mark* family, labels multiple marks correctly work. Initialisation function now take reorder argument specify whether reorder numeric values. #126 Added e_register_theme register global theme, see #127. e_theme_custom now accepts path JSON file. e_visual_map drops NAs. Added e_axis_stagger function stagger x axis labels.

title: echarts4r 0.2.3
text: CRAN release: 2019-07-18 Bar chart’s bind argument fixed. e_tooltip_choro_formatter tooltip formatter choropleth maps added, thanks Artem. Tooltip formatters correctly identify locale UNIX systems, thanks Artem. e_mark_point(), e_mark_line() e_mark_area() longer use grep(), means serie matched exact name. Thanks @shrektan reporting PR (#80, #81). Multiple e_title now allowed. Multiple e_visual_map timelines now fixed. Corrected links (think). e_sankey fix thanks Artem Klevtsov. Many dependencies removed, now much easier install.

title: echarts4r 0.2.2
text: CRAN release: 2019-04-09 draw argument added e_charts, set whether draw chart, see bullet . e_draw_p added choose draw chart. e_inspect inspect output echarts4r. echarts_from_json create echarts4r object JSON options. e_axis family functions (e.g.: e_x_axis) now accepts column name first argument easily adapt range axes, similar fashion e_visual_map. e_charts family forces data.frame conversion avoid jsonlite bug. Fixed bug formatter argument e_tooltip passing custom function working.

title: echarts4r 0.2.1
text: CRAN release: 2019-01-05 Support timeline added e_clean removed use anymore. e_list added pas raw list options. Improved e_color_range helper. e_lm & e_loess now support group_by. e_scattter scaling much robust new arguments. Also takes optional symbol argument. Jitter points e_scatter e_append adapated work new scatter-family function (scaling). e_lines_gl added. Improved examples. Can now register multiple maps e_map_regiter. Error handling e_loess e_lm better work groups. e_capture capture events implemented. e_bands add confidence bands. Added example heatmap geo. Fixed bug background color applied e_color. e_scatter size forced numeric avoid buggy character vector caused apply function. Forces webgl rendering e_globe, e_scatter_gl e_flow_gl. Groups now ordered order ensure match across series using timeline = TRUE. e_theme now also accepts default. auritus theme added. bar.width argument renamed bar_width e_histogram. e_map_3d e_map correctly assign name argument. Axis tooltip formatters helpers added e_tooltip_item_formatter & e_axis_formatter, thanks Artem Klevtsov. e_error_bar added plot error bars. Ability specify icons e_legend. e_aria added enable generating Accessible Rich Internet Applications.

title: echarts4r 0.2.0
text: CRAN release: 2018-11-14 Arguments containing . replaced _ clarity. .e.: coord.system => coord_system. Deprecated functions 0.1.2 removed, can found echarts4r.assets package: e_convert_texture e_stars_texture e_composite_texture e_globe_texture e_map_texture scatter family function reworked: scale argument now takes scaling function. accomodate , e_visual_map function also takes, optionally, scaling function. Retired e_keras_history due uselessness.

title: echarts4r 0.1.2
text: e_labels easily add labels. Mapbox support see e_mapbox. Improved e_scatter. Improved e_toolbox. Fixed e_axis (corresponding e_x_axis e_y_axis) bugs. e_add added nested data. e_showtip_p e_hidetip_p fixed. e_focus_adjacency_p e_unfocus_adjacency_p proxies highlight adjacent nodes (graph/network) added. Deprecation texture related functions favour echarts4r.assets. e_single_axis added, works e_scatter. e_text_style added, customise global fonts. e_angle_axis now takes serie argument, see example. Improved documentation many functions. e_common pass options apply subsequent charts. First iteration graphic low-level API: g_graphic_g g_group_g g_image_g g_text_g g_rect_g g_circle_g g_ring_g g_sector_g g_arc_g g_polygon_g g_polyline_g g_line_g g_bezier_curve_g Added actions can tied buttons. Added ability add buttons. Added e_arrange & e_connect connect charts interactions visualise together. Better supprot radial, angle, polar charts. Callbacks added e_on e_off. e_map_custom added work custom registered maps. e_datazoom takes toolbox argument optionally dataZoom toolbox element. Much improved documentation e_map e_map_3d longer require serie argument. e_mark_*: serie argument mark family functions (.e.: e_mark_point) can now take vector left NULL point marked series.

title: echarts4r 0.1.1
text: CRAN release: 2018-09-17 Now available CRAN longer passes entirety data.frame fron-end.

title: echarts4r 0.1.0
text: echarts4r now understands dplyr::group_by e_clean remove original data visualisation lighten end product.

title: echarts4r 0.0.2
text: e_keras_history added - plot keras history (loss & acc). e_format_axis, e_format_x_axis, e_format_y_axis added - format axis labels & pointers. e_tooltip now takes default trigger = "item". e_flip_coords added - flip x/y corrdinates. Grid & Axis vignettes. e_register_map fixed. renderer argument added e_charts enable SVG renderer.

title: echarts4r 0.0.1
text: Added: e_lm, e_glm e_loess.
